This FP can be viewed alternatively as the FP of pure gravity,
slightly shifted due to the presence of a free, massless, minimally
coupled scalar, or as the Gaussian FP of the pure scalar theory,
generalized to include gravitational interactions.  It is remarkable
that matter remains "non-self-interacting" at this FP, and that the
only nonzero couplings are those that affect only the gravitational
degrees of freedom.  
(This goes some way towards justifying the assumption in 
 that matter fields are non-self-interacting.)
For want of a better terminology, we shall refer
to this FP as the Gaussian-Matter FP, of GMFP for short.

The issue arises whether the coupled system of equations
admits other nontrivial FP's.
The complexity of the equations has prevented us from
deriving definite results on this issue.
We have looked for other FP's using numerical methods
in a five-parameter truncation of the theory containing
the couplings  for  and the couplings
 for .
Our method consists in considering a grid in the space of all
parameters, evaluating the beta functions by numerical integration at
a point and then at all neighboring points.  If all beta functions
change sign simultaneously when going from a point to a neighbor,
then generically there will be a FP somewhere 
near the link between the two points. The region is then examined with
a finer grid until the position of the FP is located with sufficient
accuracy.
We have started off with the  grid given by  and
, confirming the results of; we
have then added one by one the other variables involved in the
five-parameter truncation, getting increasingly complicated systems
of equations. 














Because of the complexity of the beta functions, the numerical
evaluation takes considerable time. The largest range we have explored
is a  grid with the dimensionless cosmological constant
 ranging from 0.010 to 0.045 in steps
of 0.005; the dimensionless Newton constant 
ranging from 0.01 to 0.06 in steps of 0.01; the dimensionless scalar
mass  ranging from -1 to 1 in steps of 0.2; the
dimensionless quartic scalar coupling  ranging from -15
to 5 in steps of 1; the dimensionless scalar-tensor coupling
 ranging from -5 to 5 in steps of 1.  This makes a
lattice with more than 120,000 points. Many other attempts have been
tried with finer lattices and/or fewer parameters. 
We did find some nontrivial solutions when considering less than 5
parameters, but none of them survived the addition of an extra
parameter, so that we had to conclude that they were all spurious FPs 
due to the truncation. 
As a further check we have also resorted to series expansions around 
the GMFP or one of the spurious FP mentioned above. 
All the results obtained in this way are perfectly consistent
with the other calculations.
The outcome of all these efforts is that no FP other than the GMFP was found.




This is of course not a proof that an FP does not exist in this range
of couplings. For example, a beta function may change sign twice on
a link, once from positive to negative and once from negative to
positive, and if the distance between the zeroes is smaller than the
size of the step, it may well escape detection by our methods.
Nevertheless, after this numerical work, we consider it quite unlikely
that another nontrivial FP exists in the range of values for the
couplings that we have considered.

This result is corroborated by the following observation.
If one does not
truncate the functions  and  to polynomials, as in the pure
scalar case the structure of the beta functions seems to allow
for a recursive solution depending on two free parameters.  If we fix
arbitrary values for  and , from equations
(,) one derives
 and ; substituting them into equations
(,), one can solve for
 and  and so on.  This will determine the functions
 and  up to two arbitrary parameters. It will be
interesting to analyze this in detail and to see whether the resulting
functions  and  are regular or still present the problems
discussed in.
In any case, it seems highly unlikely that the solutions will
be polynomial.
This point of view also sheds a different light on the FP
found in. The values of
 and  at the GMFP are the only ones for
which  and , and as a consequence all the higher
couplings turn out to be zero, in accordance with the truncation
made there.  We shall not pursue this issue anymore here.  In the
rest of this paper we shall restrict our attention to the GMFP, which
is a special member of this family of solutions, and is definitely a
physically acceptable solution.



