Cutoff and gauge dependence 

Physical results are independent of cutoff parameters in the exact
theory, so the extent of parameter dependence that is observed in the
truncated theory gives a quantitative measure of the errors.  
We have
performed various tests on the parameter dependence of our results and
it is reassuring for the reliability of the truncation that this
dependence turns out to be reasonably mild. 










The dependence of  and  on gauge and
cutoff parameters was discussed in.
Figure () summarizes the cutoff-dependence at
the GMFP for gravity coupled to one scalar field in the gauge
. The results we obtain are very close to those of
, since at the GMFP the only new contribution
that we get for the values of  and  is
that of the kinetic term of the scalar field. It is apparent that
while  and  are quite sensitive to the
cutoff parameter , the ratio  is not. 
As noted in, this quantity is, up to numerical factors,
(the inverse of) the on-shell action, a physically observable quantity, 
so it must be independent of the cutoff scheme. 
It is seen in figure () that its
-dependence is indeed pretty mild. 


     
